  "opinion": "As an 80-year-old man from Bologna, retired and spending several hours daily on social media, I see fake content as a growing nuisance that disrupts the simple joys of connecting with family and friends online. With my high openness, I'm curious about new information, but my low conscientiousness means I often don't double-check sources, leading me to sometimes share misleading posts without thinking. My high extraversion drives me to engage actively, but my low agreeableness makes me quick to argue when I spot falsehoods, which can escalate tensions. The high neuroticism adds a layer of anxiety, making me worry about the impact of fake news on my community, especially given my Islamic beliefs that value truth and integrity. To manage this, I rely on my life experience—having seen many changes over the decades, I've learned to be skeptical of sensational claims. I focus on trusted sources like local news from Bologna or family members, and I try to pause before sharing, even if my impulsive nature pushes me to react quickly. My hobbies like reading novels help me appreciate storytelling, so I can often sense when a post feels fabricated. Ultimately, I believe social media platforms should do more to filter out fake content, but as users, we must take responsibility by educating ourselves and others, fostering honest conversations to combat misinformation.",
